---

<Base title={`${post.title} — xNet`} description={post.description}>
  <Nav />

  <main>
    <RecordHero
      title={post.title}
      deck={post.description}
      date={formatPostDate(post.pubDate)}
      readingMinutes={post.readingMinutes}
      tags={post.tags}
    />

    <article
      class="prose prose-lg mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16 dark:prose-invert prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-indigo-600 dark:prose-a:text-indigo-400"
    >
      <Byline post={post} />

      <p>
        In 2004 a software engineer in the north-east of England put a website
        online. It was pink and white. Its mascot was a cartoon pig. Its name —
        Oink’s Pink Palace — sounded like a children’s programme, and to join it
        you needed an invitation from someone already inside, who was staking a
        little of their own standing on your behaviour. It ran for three years,
        gathered roughly a hundred and eighty thousand members, and became, by
        the reckoning of the people who used it, the most complete collection of
        recorded music anywhere on the internet.
      </p>
      <p>
        It was also, in the eyes of the law, a machine for copyright
        infringement on an industrial scale, and in October 2007 it was raided
        by British and Dutch police and switched off. We will get to that —
        honestly, because the ending is half the lesson. But start where the
        people who were there start. When the raid made the news, Trent Reznor
        of Nine Inch Nails admitted he’d had an account, and described the site
        as being “like the world’s greatest record store.” Not the world’s
        biggest download button. A <em>record store</em> — a place staffed by
        people who know the stock, argue about pressings, and light up when you
        ask for something obscure.
      </p>
      <p>
        This essay is about what made that pink website feel more alive than
        platforms with a thousand times its budget — and what a piece of
        software that wants that feeling, without the felony, should actually
        build. It ends, as these essays do, with what we took from it when we
        built <a href="/">xNet</a>. But the first thing to understand is that
        the Palace’s magic was not the music. It was the <em>mechanics</em>.
      </p>

      <h2>A commons with a quality bar</h2>
      <p>
        Three rules did most of the work.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>You had to give to take.</strong> Every account carried a ratio
        of uploaded to downloaded bytes, and if you only ever took, your
        account withered. The genius of the ratio was that generosity could be
        <em>passive</em>: you left your client open, and while you slept your
        machine quietly served the albums you loved to strangers who wanted
        them. Thousands of people, seeding constantly, in the background of
        their lives. Rare records stayed alive for years because keeping them
        alive cost each member almost nothing and meant something anyway.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The bar was high, and the community held it.</strong> Transcodes
        — re-encoding a lossy file and passing it off as better — were banned.
        Rips were checked. If you uploaded something shoddy, people told you,
        the way a record-store clerk winces at a scratched sleeve. The quality
        standard wasn’t a moderation policy imposed from above; it was the
        community’s pride, enforced laterally, member to member. Getting a rip
        right was a small craft, and the craft was the culture.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The boundary meant something.</strong> Invitations flowed
        through people, so every member was vouched for by a chain of humans
        stretching back to the beginning. And inside the boundary, the norms
        got delightfully specific — the site famously required members to have
        cute avatars. That detail is easy to laugh at and important to take
        seriously: it was a community confident enough in its own character to
        legislate whimsy. Kitsch was the border fence. If pink offended you,
        you were free to leave, and the pig didn’t miss you.
      </p>
      <p>
        A political economist would recognise all of this instantly. Elinor
        Ostrom spent a career documenting how communities govern shared
        resources without markets or states, and distilled eight design
        principles from hundreds of cases: clear boundaries, locally-fitted
        rules, collective choice, community monitoring, graduated sanctions,
        cheap conflict resolution, recognition by outside authority, nested
        governance. The Palace and its descendants hit the list almost
        point-for-point — the invite tree is a boundary, the visible ratio is
        monitoring, the warning-before-ban ladder is graduated sanctions.
        Nobody involved had read Ostrom. A few thousand music obsessives,
        governing a commons, rediscovered her principles from scratch, because
        those are the shapes that work.
      </p>
      <p>
        Almost the whole list. Hold that thought.
      </p>

      <h2>The refinement, and the anxiety</h2>
      <p>
        When the Palace fell, its community did not disperse. Within
        <em>four days</em>, ex-members had launched What.CD, which over the
        next nine years refined every mechanic the Palace had sketched.
        Admission now ran through a live interview about ripping, transcoding
        and spectral analysis — an entire third-party site existed just to
        coach applicants. Inferior rips could be “trumped” by better ones. The
        staff wrote their own tracker software and open-sourced it, and it
        still powers much of that world today. By 2010 the collection had hit
        a million torrents; the eulogies later called it a library of
        Alexandria, and they weren’t reaching. It was very likely the most
        complete music archive ever assembled, built entirely by volunteers,
        governed entirely by its own rules.
      </p>
      <p>
        But the refinement sharpened an edge that had always been there. On a
        site that well-seeded, most members mathematically <em>could not</em>
        upload enough to improve their ratio — everyone was already seeding
        everything. Users invented a name for the resulting condition:
        <em>ratio anxiety</em>. Researchers who measured these communities
        found extraordinary performance — download speeds dozens of times
        higher than public trackers — and, in the same data, a full-blown
        credit economy with deflationary pathologies, hoarding, and dread.
        The economists’ verdict is the one worth keeping: enforced ratio is
        not a gift economy. It is a <em>scoreboard</em> economy, and the
        scoreboard slowly eats the gift.
      </p>
      <p>
        Lewis Hyde, in <em>The Gift</em>, put his finger on why decades before
        any tracker existed: a gift only remains a gift while it moves freely;
        price it, meter it, hoard it, and the thing that made it binding
        evaporates. The seeding itself — leaving your machine on overnight so
        a stranger in another hemisphere can hear a record — was one of the
        purest gift economies the internet ever produced. The ratio that
        <em>enforced</em> it was already the beginning of its corruption. Any
        system that wants the loop has to decide what to do about the ledger.
      </p>

      <HonestRecord />

      <h2>The missing principle</h2>
      <p>
        Now the ending. In October 2007, following a two-year investigation by
        the record-industry bodies, police raided the Palace’s servers in
        Amsterdam and arrested its founder at his father’s house. He was
        charged with conspiracy to defraud — the first prosecution of its kind
        in Britain — and in January 2010 a jury acquitted him unanimously. The
        site never came back. In November 2016, French police seized What.CD’s
        servers; the staff shut the site down within hours and destroyed the
        databases themselves rather than let member data fall into anyone
        else’s hands. The greatest record store in the world went out the way
        it had lived: protecting its members first. And nine years of
        painstaking, volunteer-built archive — the interviews, the trumped
        rips, the liner notes, the forum threads — vanished in an afternoon.
      </p>
      <p>
        Go back to Ostrom’s list. The tracker communities aced boundaries,
        monitoring, sanctions, self-governance. The principle they could never
        have was the seventh: <em>recognition of the right to organise</em> —
        the outside world’s agreement that your commons is allowed to exist.
        Their content guaranteed they’d never get it. But notice that the
        <em>failure mode</em> — everything lives on servers someone else can
        seize — has nothing to do with infringement. Geocities died this way.
        Google Reader died this way. Every Discord server, every subreddit,
        every group chat your scene lives in today sits on machines that can
        be sold, sunset, or subpoenaed by people who have never heard of you.
        The best offer the modern platform makes is the one in Mastodon’s
        server covenant: three months’ notice before your world ends. A
        gentler eviction is still an eviction.
      </p>
      <p>
        The lesson of the Palace is not “don’t host infringing content,”
        though, yes. The lesson is that <strong>a community’s ethos is only
        as durable as its worst day</strong>, and on the worst day, what
        matters is where the data physically lives. Ostrom’s seventh principle
        can be granted by a state — or it can be made moot by architecture.
        If every member of the scene already holds the archive, there is
        nothing left to raid.
      </p>

      <h2>Scenes, and what they run on</h2>
      <p>
        Brian Eno coined a word for what the Palace had: <em>scenius</em> —
        “genius, only embedded in a scene rather than in genes.” Kevin Kelly,
        unpacking the idea, listed the conditions that nurture it: mutual
        appreciation, where risky moves are applauded and subtlety is noticed;
        rapid exchange of tools and techniques, where anything invented is
        immediately shared; success claimed by the whole scene; and a
        surrounding world tolerant enough not to crush the weirdness. His
        examples were Bloomsbury, Building 20 at MIT, Xerox PARC. He could
        have been describing a tracker forum at two in the morning: the rip
        guides, the interview-prep sites, the arguments about spectrals — a
        community teaching itself a craft and flaunting every advance.
      </p>
      <p>
        Scenes still form constantly — on Discord, on Reddit, in group chats,
        in the unlisted corners writers call the cozyweb. What they lack is
        not energy. It’s <em>ground</em>. They rent their corner of space-time
        from landlords with other priorities, they can’t take their history
        with them when they go, and their tools — the shared crate, the
        collective log, the common archive — have to be improvised out of
        screenshots and pasted links. The scene has no data layer. The
        fourth of Kelly’s conditions, protection from the outside, is exactly
        the one a rented room cannot provide.
      </p>

      <h2>What we took</h2>
      <p>
        xNet is built to be that ground, and the Palace is all over its
        design — harvested, we hope, with the honesty box above kept in view.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The loop, without the leaderboard.</strong> The reciprocity
        that made the Palace hum is structural in a local-first network:
        holding a replica of your scene’s space is passive generosity, the
        way seeding was — your device keeps the archive alive just by being
        in the scene. What we refuse is the scoreboard. Stewardship should be
        <em>legible</em> — “this space lives on nine devices; yours is one” —
        and never <em>scored</em>. No ratios, no ranks, no streaks. That rule
        is enforced the same way our other <a href="/commitments">charter
        commitments</a> are: a CI gate fails any build that introduces ratio
        scorekeeping, right next to the rule that bans streak counters. The
        difference between “your device kept this alive for 340 days” and
        “you are #14 in this space” is the difference between a thank-you and
        a debt.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Vibe belongs to the scene.</strong> The Palace was pink
        because its people made it pink. The protocol underneath — BitTorrent
        — was calm grey plumbing with no opinion about pigs. That division of
        labour is the right one, and we wrote it into the design system as
        doctrine: the venue stays quiet — monochrome chrome, hairline borders,
        warmth as a choice — so that every scene can be as loud, as kitsch,
        as <em>itself</em> as it likes. xNet should never have a vibe
        monopoly. Two scenes on it should feel as different as a record store
        and a farm co-op, and both should feel safe in exactly the same way.
        Even our demo workspace now ships with a scene in it — a little
        record-archiving collective, crates and liner notes and a
        pressing-quality checklist — because the first thing you see in a
        tool teaches you what it’s for, and we’d rather you meet a scene than
        a fictional corporation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The scene outlives the server.</strong> This is the one the
        Palace couldn’t have, and it’s the deepest promise in the stack. Your
        identity is a key you generate, not an account someone issues. Every
        change is signed and chained in a log you hold. The archive your
        scene builds is on your scene’s devices — the hub is a convenience,
        not a home. If any server dies — seized, sunset, or simply
        unplugged — every member walks away with the whole commons and the
        keys to re-home it. You can raid the palace; everyone leaves with a
        copy. We’ve written before about <a href="/blog/the-right-to-say-no">
        the right to say no</a> and <a href="/blog/the-vault-and-the-view">
        apps as views, not vaults</a>; this is those essays with a pig
        mascot: exit is not a feature of the product, it is the product.
      </p>

      <h2>Infrastructure for the scene you love</h2>
      <p>
        There’s a word lately for the future this points at — solarpunk: the
        insistence that the hopeful timeline is a buildable one, and that it
        starts with infrastructure. One of the movement’s founding essays
        opens with a mayor’s line worth carrying around:
        dealing with infrastructure is a protection against being robbed of
        one’s self-determination. That is the Palace’s story compressed to a
        sentence — a community that had everything except infrastructure it
        was allowed to keep.
      </p>
      <p>
        So picture the scenes that deserve better ground. A farming
        collective spread across three continents, accumulating seasons of
        planting data for themselves and for the commons. A film crew cutting
        a documentary across nine time zones. A fandom archiving a
        vanishing art form — legally, this time, with the artists in the
        room. Each one wants what the Palace had: a boundary that means
        something, a quality bar held with pride, reciprocity that runs in
        the background like a heartbeat, and a corner of space-time that is
        genuinely, durably <em>theirs</em>. None of that requires anyone’s
        permission any more. The mechanics were never the illegal part.
      </p>
      <p>
        Somewhere in England there is a man who, for three years, ran the
        world’s greatest record store out of a rented server and a pink
        website with a pig on it. The courts settled what he wasn’t guilty
        of. What he was guilty of — proving that a few thousand people who
        love something can out-build an industry, for nothing, for the joy of
        it — has no statute of limitations. Build your scene. Keep your own
        log. Hold the quality bar because you care, not because anyone’s
        counting. And if your palace wants to be pink: mandatory cute
        avatars. We’ll smile.
      </p>

